@53 2.12 Translating and starting a program
@54 4 steps in transforming a C program in non-volatile
storage into program running on computer
@55 compiler
@56 assembler
@57 linker
@58 loader
@59 transforms C programs into assembly program
@5a assembly language: symbolic language that can be translated into machine code
@5b pseudo-instructions: common variation of assembly instruction often treated
as if it were an instruction in its own right
@5c simplifies translation and programming
@5d assembly program to object file
@5e object file: combo of machine language, data, and info to place
instructions in memory
@5f symbol table: table that matches names of labels to address
of the memory words that the instructions occupy
@5g unix object file components
@5h object file header
@5i text segment
@5j static data segment
@5k relocation information
@5l debugging info
@5m linker/link editor: syusmtes program that combiles independently
assembled machine language programs and resolves all
undefined labels into an executable file
@5n linker steps
@5o place code and data in memory
@5p determine address of data and instruction labels
@5q patch internal external refs
@5r produces executable file that can be run on computer
@5s executable file
@5t object file format
@5u no unresolved refs
@5v can contain symbol tables / debug info, stripped EXEs do not
@5w relocation info may be included for loader
